"title": "Numbers 1-20",
"content": "My name is Adam. I am in my classroom with my friends Ali and Sarah. Today, our teacher Ms Lana teaches us about numbers. Ms. Lana says, 'Good morning, everyone! Today we learn numbers from 1 to 20.' She holds up one finger and says, 'This is number 1. Say it with me: one.' We all say, 'One!' Then she holds up two fingers. 'This is number 2. Say: two.' We say, 'Two!' Ms. Lana writes on the board: 1 one, 2 two, 3 three, 4 four, 5 five. She says, 'Repeat after me: three, four, five.' We repeat, 'Three, four, five.' Sarah raises her hand. Ms. Lana says, 'Yes, Sarah?' Sarah asks, 'How do we say 6, 7, 8?' Ms. Lana smiles. 'Good question! Six, seven, eight.' She writes them on the board. 'Now, let's count together from 1 to 8.' We count: 'One, two, three, four, five, six, seven, eight.' Ali says, 'I know nine and ten! Nine, ten!' Ms. Lana says, 'Very good, Ali! Yes, nine and ten.' She continues, 'Now numbers 11 to 20. Listen carefully: eleven, twelve, thirteen, fourteen, fifteen, sixteen, seventeen, eighteen, nineteen, twenty.' She points to each number on the board. We try to repeat. It is a little difficult, but we practice. Ms. Lana gives us an activity. She says, 'Look at your desk. How many pencils do you have?' I look at my desk. I have two pencils. I say, 'I have two pencils.' Sarah says, 'I have three pencils.' Ali says, 'I have one pencil.' Ms. Lana asks, 'How many books are on my desk?' We look. There are five books on her desk. We answer together, 'Five books!' Ms. Lana claps. 'Very good! Now, let's count our fingers. Hold up your hands.' We hold up our hands. Ms. Lana says, 'How many fingers do you have on one hand?' Sarah says, 'Five!' Ms. Lana says, 'Yes! And on two hands?' Ali counts, 'Five and five is ten! Ten fingers.' Ms. Lana nods. 'Excellent! Now, let's count from 1 to 20 one more time.' We all count together: 'One, two, three, four, five, six, seven, eight, nine, ten, eleven, twelve, thirteen, fourteen, fifteen, sixteen, seventeen, eighteen, nineteen, twenty!' Ms. Lana says, 'Great job, class! You learn very well.' At the end of the lesson, Ms. Lana says, 'For homework, practice numbers 1 to 20 with your family.' I feel happy. Numbers are fun!",
